Hey, Barry, what gives? There are a couple of vets who want to explore some avenue, some aspects of their Vietnam experiences, in a different format and you want to thump them on the head for it? Frankly, I don't know if I want to be a part of it or not at this time, more because of timing and things going in my own life, but, if it works for at least one on the site, it may benefit even more lurkers. Who knows?<br><br>
As far as the running battles between you, Cook and Edward, ain't it getting tiring. Hell, there are things with which they posture that I don't agree with, anymore than there are things which you postulate with which I do not agree with, but, what the fuck, over. It's getting real old, the arguments for both extremes has been voiced many times before, and honestly, none of you have said anything new that holds my interest. This is not a slap in the face of any involved, for those new to the site have the right to vent, to express themselves, to defend their positions, their beliefs, as so many of us have done in the past, but you have been around the block already.<br><br>
And need I bite you on the ass of diminishing one having pride in his cultural and ethnic heritage. Shit, we have been around that block before, also.<br><br>
Maybe it's time for us old fogeys to move over and let the newer members of this site have a go at it. <br><br>
Ed, I will watch your new thread with interest, but frankly, I am at a space right now where I could contribute little to it. Maybe at some point I'll jump in, but not at the get go. I wish it luck.<br><br>
As far as giving me a Lakota handle, I am honoured, however, I carry my current handle with pride as it was bestowed on me by my platoon oh so many years ago. I take pride in the role I played as a medic during the war and after, as a paramedic. This is who I am. I appreciate the thought however, and hope you take no offense.
